line=82 fonts=F0-12.0 bbox=108.0,655.0,541.33,667.0                    :       In this respect, the subject of the adjective does not act like a direct object, but rather like
line=83 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.28 bbox=108.0,643.0,541.33,655.0        :       the subject of  an agentive clause.  In  other words, the  verbal passive acts like an
line=84 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.27 bbox=108.0,631.0,540.25,643.0        :       unaccusative predicate, whereas the adjectival passives acts like an unergative predicate.
line=85 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.13 bbox=108.0,619.0,540.85,631.0        :       Moreover,  this configuration of facts proves to be quite general:  It is also found in
line=86 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.27 bbox=108.0,607.0,541.46,619.0        :       adjectives derived from intransitive verbs in Italian, and in adjectives derived by affixes
line=87 fonts=F0-12.0,F2-12.0 iscore=0.31 bbox=108.0,595.0,539.92,607.0:       cognate  to -able (Cinque 1990).  Borer  and Grodzinsky   1986 replicates this contrast
line=88 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.29 bbox=107.99,583.0,539.7,595.0        :       between  verbal passives and adjectival passives in Hebrew with pairs like (6), where the
line=89 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.25 bbox=107.99,571.0,541.07,583.0       :       test for unaccusativity is whether a dative clitic can be understood as the possessor of the
line=90 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.12 bbox=107.99,559.0,176.32,571.0       :       subject or not.

