line=339 fonts=F0-12.0,F2-12.0 bbox=107.99,643.0,540.77,655.0            :       This is what one would  expect if be is a mere auxiliary, whereas ye plays an important
line=340 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.29 bbox=107.99,631.0,520.9,643.0         :       semantic function tailored to the particular needs of adjectives as a syntactic category.
line=341 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.25 bbox=143.99,619.0,539.46,631.0        :              In conclusion, then, it is the existence of a null Pred head in the grammar of
line=342 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.12 bbox=107.99,607.0,541.42,619.0        :       English that blurs the difference between verbs  and adjectives in contexts like (19).
line=343 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.12 bbox=107.99,595.0,539.08,607.0        :       However,  the fact that Pred happens to be null is presumably an accident of English and
line=344 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.19 bbox=107.99,583.0,541.72,595.0        :       related languages. Thus in Edo, the true difference between the two categories shows up
line=345 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.07 bbox=107.99,571.0,171.3,583.0         :       more clearly.
line=346 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.00 bbox=143.99,559.0,540.84,571.0        :              We  note in passing that this theory predicts that the Edo examples in (23) should
line=347 fonts=F0-12.0,F2-12.0 iscore=0.31 bbox=107.99,547.0,540.82,559.0:       improve if the copular element yé is added to the structure. With yé present, the structure
line=348 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.25 bbox=107.99,535.0,540.91,547.0        :       would  be equivalent to (19b)/(25b) in English, with the sole difference that the Pred head
line=349 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.20 bbox=107.99,523.0,492.26,535.0        :       is overt at PF. In fact, such sentences are marginally possible, as shown in (28).

