line=442 fonts=F0-12.0,F2-12.0 bbox=108.0,559.0,540.68,571.0            :       However,  this problem is not serious. The only thing we have to say is that -ness and -ity
line=443 fonts=F0-12.0,F3-10.0 iscore=0.17 bbox=108.0,547.0,540.24,560.0:       include Chierchia’s ^{∪} operator as part of their meaning. Intuitively speaking, we claim
line=444 fonts=F0-12.0,F2-12.0 iscore=0.15 bbox=108.0,535.0,540.03,547.0:       that -ness and -ity semantically “verbalize” the roots they attach to before nominalizing
line=445 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.20 bbox=108.0,523.0,539.94,535.0        :       them.  There  is nothing impossible  about this; at most we  predict that this kind of
line=446 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.07 bbox=108.0,511.0,539.05,523.0        :       nominalization might be somewhat  marked  from a crosslinguistic perspective. However,
line=447 fonts=F0-12.0,F2-12.0 iscore=0.06 bbox=108.0,499.0,540.13,511.0:       the fact that -ness and -ity happen to have this property in English is another reason why
line=448 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.28 bbox=108.01,487.0,524.64,499.0       :       the true nature of the adjective/verb distinction is not as clear in English as it is in Edo.

