doc_id=21 page=11 block_id=11-14 bbox=108.01,79.0,541.35,187.0 label=bbbbbbbbbbbb 466 474
line=466 fonts=F0-12.0 bbox=144.01,175.0,540.21,187.0            :              Nevertheless, a closer look at the data shows that the contrast between As and Vs
line=467 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.33 bbox=108.01,163.0,540.64,175.0:       does show  in Edo in a more subtle way. Whereas  both adjectival and verbal resultative
line=468 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.33 bbox=108.01,151.0,540.85,163.0:       predicates are acceptable in simple past tense clauses, only the adjectival predicate is
line=469 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.13 bbox=108.01,139.0,540.03,151.0:       possible when the main  verb bears past perfective tense, as shown in (36a). When the
line=470 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.31 bbox=108.01,127.0,540.63,139.0:       resultative predicate is a stative verb, the first verb cannot be in the past perfective form,
line=471 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.25 bbox=108.01,115.0,541.35,127.0:       regardless of whether past perfective morphology also appears on the second  verb, as
line=472 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.14 bbox=108.01,103.0,540.69,115.0:       shown  in (36b).  (The  direct objects are clefted in these examples because the past
line=473 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.21 bbox=108.01,91.0,539.74,103.0 :       perfective affix elides before overt NPs as a result of fairly normal phonological rules
line=474 fonts=F0-12.0 iscore=0.14 bbox=108.01,79.0,193.33,91.0  :       (Agheyisi 1990)).

