doc_id=21 page=14 block_id=14-10 bbox=72.0,56.0,504.39,122.0 label=bbb 608 613
line=608 fonts=F0-10.0,F0-8.0 bbox=72.0,111.0,503.84,122.0           :^{3}Another clear syntactic difference between stative verbs and similar adjectives is that only adjectives can
line=609 fonts=F0-10.0 iscore=0.20 bbox=72.0,100.0,504.15,110.0      :directly modify nouns in a distinctive attributive construction, whereas stative verbs can modify nouns only
line=610 fonts=F0-10.0,F2-10.0 iscore=0.22 bbox=72.0,89.0,504.39,99.0:if they become participles or relative clauses. Thus in English one has the hungry man, the man  that
line=611 fonts=F0-10.0,F2-10.0 iscore=0.25 bbox=72.0,78.0,503.04,88.0:hungers, and the hungering man, but not *the hunger man; and the same holds true in Edo (except that Edo
line=612 fonts=F0-10.0 iscore=0.15 bbox=72.0,67.0,504.28,77.0        :has no participial morphology). See Baker 1996b  for a tentative analysis of these facts within this same
line=613 fonts=F0-10.0 iscore=0.06 bbox=72.0,56.0,181.15,66.0        :framework  of assumptions.

